# SKYETECH Sovereign Primitives — IDEia Completion Reality

## Why the IDEia work moved forward
The IDEia work moved forward because the implementation directive was executed as a **baseline parity directive**, not as a full product-completion directive.

That means the lanes were advanced after they met this line:
- lane-owned module structure exists
- workspace browsing works
- file read/write works
- runtime start/stop/log controls work
- state persists
- full-app launch back to the original product works

That is a real milestone.

It is **not** the same thing as saying the lane is fully built out to final enterprise scope.

---

## What was actually completed

### Shared baseline work completed
- shared SkyeCDE bridge client
- shared workspace/file/runtime shell
- persistent lane state
- launch mapping back to original products
- lane-owned shell/config/runtime/session/layout modules for all four IDEias

### Lane parity completed
- SkyDexia baseline parity
- SuperIDEia baseline parity
- SkaixuProIDEia baseline parity
- KaixuSuperIDEia baseline parity

---

## What is still not complete

### 1. Product-native enterprise depth
Each IDEia still needs its own deeper product-specific workflows.

Examples:
- product-native panels
- product-native command systems
- product-native task and automation flows
- product-native recovery/admin/operator lanes
- product-native deployment and governance flows

### 2. SkyeHawk integration
The IDEias are not yet fully wired into one shared SkyeHawk system.

What is still needed:
- shared route registry
- hidden-command support in SkyeCDE and IDEias
- visible launcher standardization
- role-aware route filtering

### 3. Cross-platform governance depth
The lanes still need more than bridge-backed controls.

Still needed:
- sovereign event integration for system-menu actions
- policy-aware route exposure
- recovery/admin route governance
- deeper platform-specific security behavior

### 4. Product-facing maturity language
The docs need to stop using wording that sounds like total completion when the actual state is baseline parity.

---

## Correct language going forward

### Accurate
- verified baseline lane
- parity-complete support layer
- lane-owned module structure complete
- original-product-preserving upgrade lane

### Not accurate yet
- fully built enterprise IDE
- complete product-native replacement
- fully finished upgraded platform

---

## What has to happen before the IDEias can be called fully built

1. Each lane needs product-native workflow expansion.
2. SkyeHawk needs to be wired in as the shared system-menu layer.
3. Admin, recovery, operator, and governance routes need to be real.
4. The lane needs deeper feature ownership beyond the shared shell baseline.
5. The lane needs verification against those deeper product-specific features.

---

## Bottom line
The IDEias are not fake placeholders anymore.

But they are also not honestly at full final enterprise completion yet.

The real state is:
- baseline parity is complete
- full enterprise buildout is still ahead

That is the distinction that should be used from here forward.